rld political order. This volume of original essays focuses on the origins and current status of the new African states and one Arab-African state, Egypt. Despite their many distinguishing features, the new nations all have in common the colonial experience, which has formulated their major political attributes. The eminent authors of these studies describe the structural problems of new states, particularly the role of ideology, the patterns of internal conflict, and the character of political cleavages. Of special concern are the ways in which international organization induced the formation of new states and, conversely, the impact the new nations have had on the international system. The resulting conflicts require redefinition of the international order, a new kind of regulation. This book takes a major step on the road to such redefinition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGründung. 0aPolitical science. 0aPolitik. 0aPolitisches System. 0aStaat. 0aUnabhängigkeitsbewegung. 0aWeltordnung. 4aAfrica -- Politics and government. 4aNewly independent states -- Politics and government. 4aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aClaude, Jr., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, James S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawford Young, M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutsch, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Willard R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKilson, Martin, econtributor.4